solution:
Let \(T\) be an anti-Pascal pyramid with \(n\) rows, containing every integer from 1 to \(1+2+\cdots+n\), and let \(a_{1}\) be the topmost number in \(T\) (Figure 1). The two numbers below \(a_{1}\) are some \(a_{2}\) and \(b_{2}=a_{1}+a_{2}\), the two numbers below \(b_{2}\) are some \(a_{3}\) and \(b_{3}=a_{1}+a_{2}+a_{3}\), and so on and so forth all the way down to the bottom row, where some \(a_{n}\) and \(b_{n}=a_{1}+a_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\) are the two neighbours below \(b_{n-1}=a_{1}+a_{2}+\cdots+a_{n-1}\). Since the \(a_{k}\) are \(n\) pairwise distinct positive integers whose sum does not exceed the largest number in \(T\), which is \(1+2+\cdots+n\), it follows that they form a permutation of \(1,2, \ldots, n\).
